          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2020-11-30 18:50:49.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Verified+1\n\nPassed enforced test review-dne-selinux-ssk on CentOS 7.8/x86_64 uploaded by Trevis Autotest from trevis-21vm5: https://testing.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/417393bc-2aa5-4795-889b-83a30fbc0403 ran 6 tests.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "95a7f34498565aebfb1a7651a51197f920f0e364",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2020-12-01 17:10:04.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> How does sending an RPC with a bad field size translate to -ENOENT\n > returns on the client? Is there some room for further improvement\n > here?\n\nI can't say I fully understand the mechanism here, but one possibility is for a striped directory it may be that a newly-mounted client doesn't get the any layout for the directory due to the zero-length reply buffer, it tries to do the name lookup in the DNE master directory without success, until another RPC reply (for a regular file or directory) comes in to update the minimum buffer size?  This check is ensuring that there is always *some* space allocated for the layout reply buffer. \n\nIn any case, this is restoring code that existed for a long time, and has been shown to resolve this issue at a customer site, and is extremely low risk.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
